# Quest and Event Design — Thiên Nam Engine

> Rules for designing quests, events, encounters, and world activities that produce both narrative text and game data.

---

## Core Principle: Every Event Is Dual-Natured

Every quest and event has two aspects:

1. **Narrative** — The story the player experiences (written prose)
2. **Data** — The game mechanics that make it work (JSON/TypeScript)

Both must be created together. Narrative must match data. Data must enable narrative.

---

## Event Schema

All events follow this structure:

```typescript
interface WorldEvent {
  id: string;                      // kebab-case: "world-boss-tao-giao"
  name: string;                   // "Vạn Độc Giáo nổi dậy"
  type: EventType;                // "WORLD_BOSS" | "SEASON" | "MINIGAME" | "LORE"
  scope: Scope;                    // "SERVER" | "REGION" | "SECT" | "PERSONAL"
  region?: RegionId;              // Required for REGION scope
  faction?: FactionId;            // Optional: aligned faction
  startAt: Date;
  endAt: Date;

  narrative: {
    announcement: string;         // 2-4 sentences, public log format
    progress: string[];            // Array of progress messages
    completion: string;            // Summary of outcome
    failure?: string;             // If event can fail
  };

  effects: EventEffect[];         // Game effects while active

  rewards: EventReward[];          // What players can earn

  requirements: EventRequirement;  // Who can participate

  choices?: EventChoice[];         // Player decision points

  logs: EventLogConfig;            // How to announce
}

interface EventEffect {
  type: "BUFF" | "DEBUFF" | "SPAWN" | "UNLOCK" | "CLOSE";
  target: "PLAYER" | "SECT" | "REGION" | "ALL";
  effect: {
    cultivationSpeed?: number;
    encounterRate?: number;
    dropRate?: number;
    bossId?: string;
    regionId?: string;
    unlockContent?: string;
  };
}

interface EventReward {
  type: "CURRENCY" | "ITEM" | "TITLE" | "REPUTATION";
  currency?: { type: string; amount: number };
  item?: { itemId: string; chance: number };
  title?: { id: string; name: string };
  reputation?: { factionId: string; amount: number };
}

interface EventRequirement {
  realmMin?: RealmId;
  realmMax?: RealmId;
  sectRequired?: boolean;
  regionRequired?: RegionId;
  questCompleted?: string;
}
```

---

## Event Design Checklist

Before an event is added to the database:

- [ ] Has narrative text for all states (announce, progress, complete, fail)
- [ ] Has game data that matches narrative
- [ ] Rewards don't break economy (check with economy rules)
- [ ] Requirements are appropriate for target audience
- [ ] Duration is appropriate for event type
- [ ] Can be rolled back if needed
- [ ] Logged in `WorldEvent` table with full data
- [ ] Has preview in admin panel before publish

---

## Event Types

### Personal Events (Personal scope)

- Triggered by `/encounter`, `/mission`, or RNG
- Ephemeral — only the player sees it
- Can have 1-3 choices
- Rewards are minor (silver, small cultivation bonus, herbs)
- Cannot fail catastrophically

**Example:** Encountering an injured herb gatherer on the road.

### Regional Events (Region scope)

- Affect all players in a region
- Can have public log announcements
- Medium duration (1-24 hours)
- Can affect encounter rates, drop rates, spawn rare enemies

**Example:** A sandstorm in Tây Vực.

### Server Events (Server scope)

- Affect all players
- Public log announcements required
- Major duration (3-30 days)
- Can include world bosses, season themes, major lore

**Example:** Đại Hội Võ Lâm (Grand Martial Assembly).

### World Boss Events (Boss scope)

- Spawns a boss at a location
- Players can fight the boss for rewards
- Boss has HP, attack, defense — stored in DB
- Victory triggers large reward distribution
- Defeat (boss timer expires) has narrative consequence

**Example:** Hải Vương rises from the depths.

